    <h1>Half-Wave Rectifier with Sinusoidal Source - SPICE Time Domain Analysis</h1>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card&quot;>
        <h2>Circuit Components</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>V1:</strong> Sinusoidal Voltage Source SIN(0 10 50)</li>
            <li><strong>D1:</strong> 1N4001 Diode (rectifier)</li>
            <li><strong>R1:</strong> 1 kΩ (load resistor)</li>
            <li><strong>Analysis Type:</strong> Time Domain (0s to 0.12s)</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Input Signal Parameters</h2>
    <div class=&quot;ch-formula&quot;>
        SIN(Voffset Vamplitude Frequency) = SIN(0 10 50)<br>
        • DC Offset = 0V<br>
        • Peak Amplitude = 10V<br>
        • Frequency = 50 Hz (Period = 20ms)<br>
        • RMS Voltage = 10/√2 ≈ <strong>7.07V</strong>
    </div>

    <h2>Simulation Results</h2>
    <div class=&quot;ch-grid&quot;>

        <div class=&quot;ch-col blue&quot;>
            <h3>Input Signal V(in) - Red</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Full sinusoidal waveform</li>
                <li>Swings between +10V and -10V</li>
                <li>Frequency: 50 Hz (6 complete cycles in 0.12s)</li>
                <li>Period: 20 ms per cycle</li>
                <li>AC signal with zero DC component</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class=&quot;ch-col red&quot;>
            <h3>Output Signal V(out) - Blue</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Only positive half-cycles appear at output</li>
                <li>Negative half-cycles are blocked (clipped to 0V)</li>
                <li>Peak output ≈ 10V (minus diode drop ~0.7V)</li>
                <li>Pulsating DC output (unidirectional)</li>
                <li>Output frequency = Input frequency (50 Hz)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

    </div>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card green-border&quot;>
        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p style=&quot;line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;&quot;>This circuit is a <strong>Half-Wave Rectifier</strong> that converts AC input to pulsating DC output. During the positive half-cycle of the input, the diode (D1) is forward-biased and conducts, allowing current to flow through R1. During the negative half-cycle, the diode is reverse-biased and blocks current, resulting in zero output voltage. The output contains only the positive portions of the input waveform, creating a unidirectional but pulsating DC signal. The 1N4001 diode introduces a small voltage drop (~0.7V), so the actual peak output is approximately 9.3V.</p>
    </div>

    <div class=&quot;ch-card&quot; style=&quot;background-color: #e8f8f5; border-left: 4px solid #1abc9c;&quot;>
        <h2 style=&quot;color: #16a085;&quot;>Key Characteristics &amp; Applications</h2>
        <ul style=&quot;line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;&quot;>
            <li><strong>Rectification Efficiency:</strong> ~40.6% (low compared to full-wave)</li>
            <li><strong>Ripple Factor:</strong> High (1.21) - requires filtering for smooth DC</li>
            <li><strong>DC Output Voltage:</strong> Vdc = Vpeak/π ≈ 3.18V (ideal)</li>
            <li><strong>Applications:</strong> Simple power supplies, signal demodulation, peak detection</li>
            <li><strong>Limitation:</strong> Uses only 50% of input waveform (inefficient)</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

